    ],
    "equity_impact": "Shifts travel burden onto upper-primary-age children and their families, who must commute daily to the centralized site; this burden falls disproportionately on lower-income and Roma families already documented to face 2-3 times higher rates of unqualified-teacher exposure and geographic concentration in disadvantaged rural settlements, and risks triggering 'white flight' exit to alternative schools by better-resourced families, leaving the centralized site more segregated; no compensatory transport-cost or targeted-support mechanism is built into this scenario's core design.",
    "evidence_status": "contested",
    "expected_benefits": [
      "Enables full-time specialist subject teaching at the centralized upper-grade site, addressing the documented Polish problem of rural teachers commuting between multiple part-time postings.",
      "Preserves a local school presence for the youngest, most travel-vulnerable children (grades 1-4/1-6), partially mitigating the documented burden of early-morning long-distance travel for young pupils.",
      "May reduce achievement gaps associated with delayed tracking, per some international comparative literature, though this benefit's magnitude and causal attribution remain disputed."
    ],
