    "goal": "Restructure the school system so only lower grades (1-4/1-6) remain in the village while upper grades or a new ISCED2-type school are consolidated in a larger town, following the Polish 1999 structural-reform pattern of shortened primary plus centrally sited later-stage schooling.",
    "implementation_steps": [
      {
        "action": "Designate centrally-sited ISCED2-type schools and conduct capital-investment planning with realistic multi-year procurement and construction timelines, not compressed into a single year.",
        "actor": "Ministry/EMMI and tankerület centers",
        "timeline": "year 1-5"
      },
      {
        "action": "Establish statutory transport routes and subsidized service with capacity and safety audits before pupil transfer begins.",
        "actor": "Municipality and transport authority",
        "timeline": "year 2-4"
      },
      {
        "action": "Negotiate redeployment, severance, or retraining terms for teachers affected by grade-level restructuring.",
        "actor": "District center (tankerület) and teacher unions",
        "timeline": "year 2-3"
      }
    ],
    "legacy_scenario_id": "S2",
    "mechanisms": [
      "Poland's 1999 educational reform (reducing primary school from 8 to 6 years and creating larger-catchment lower-secondary schools) was explicitly designed to improve rural education quality but inadvertently reduced primary school size and triggered rural school closures as a structural side effect.",
      "Delayed secondary tracking is associated in some international comparative literature with reduced achievement gaps, though the strength and causal attribution of this association (versus other confounding system features) is disputed among comparative-education researchers.",
      "Very small rural schools cannot provide full-time employment to subject specialists, forcing teachers to commute between multiple schools; centralizing upper grades in a larger ISCED2-type site would allow full-time specialist staffing not achievable in scattered village schools.",
      "Poland's gmina-level referendum mechanism and constitutional protection of local self-determination proved effective in preventing centrally imposed closures, offering a potential model for community consent in the centralization process."
    ],
    "risks": [
      "Poland's 1999 reform was politically reversible and was in fact reversed after 17 years; without concrete cross-party entrenchment mechanisms or constitutional-level protection, Hungary's version faces similar reversal risk, especially given the documented absence of any cross-party consensus mechanism for rural school reform.",
      "Teacher redeployment under Act LII of 2023 (Status Law), which grants district centers authority to reassign teachers, may trigger the kind of mobilization seen in the Tanítanék movement if perceived as involuntary displacement without adequate consultation."
    ],
    "title": "Structural grade reorganization (lower grades stay, upper grades centralize)",
